1)Thermodynamics is the branch of physics that deals with the study of heat, work, energy, 
and the laws governing the conversion of one form of energy into another, 
along with the behavior of systems in equilibrium.

2)âœ… Thermodynamic System

A thermodynamic system is a specific quantity of matter or a region in space chosen for study,
separated from its surroundings by a real or imaginary boundary.

Types of Thermodynamic Systems
ğŸ”¹ 1. Open System

A system that can exchange both mass and energy (heat or work) with its surroundings.

Example:
Boiling water in an open pot, human body, steam turbine.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Closed System

A system that can exchange energy (heat or work) but not mass with its surroundings.

Example:
A sealed pressure cooker, gas in a piston cylinder (without leakage).

ğŸ”¹ 3. Isolated System

A system that cannot exchange either mass or energy with its surroundings.

Example:
A perfectly insulated thermos bottle (ideal case), universe (approx).


âœ… State of a System

The state of a thermodynamic system is the condition of the system at a given moment, 
described by its measurable properties such as pressure, temperature, volume, and composition.

ğŸ“Œ Important Points

A thermodynamic state is fully defined by state variables/properties
(P, V, T, internal energy, etc.)

If any of these properties changes, the state of the system changes.

When properties do not change with time, the system is said to be in thermodynamic equilibrium.


âœ… Thermodynamic Properties

Thermodynamic properties are measurable characteristics of a system that define its state, 
such as pressure, volume, temperature, and mass.

Types of Thermodynamic Properties
ğŸ”¹ 1. Intensive Properties

Properties that do not depend on the mass or size of the system.

They remain the same even if the system is divided into smaller parts.
Examples:


Temperature (T)


Pressure (P)


Density (Ï)


Specific heat


Refractive index


Concentration


Memory Trick:
Intensive = Independent of mass (I â†’ Independent)

ğŸ”¹ 2. Extensive Properties

Properties that depend on the mass or size of the system.

If the system is divided, these properties split in the same ratio.
Examples:


Mass (m)


Volume (V)


Internal energy (U)


Enthalpy (H)


Entropy (S)


Number of moles (n)


Memory Trick:
Extensive = Expands with mass (E â†’ Expands)

ğŸ“Œ Comparison Table
Property TypeDepends on Mass?ExamplesIntensiveâŒ NoTemperature, Pressure, DensityExtensiveâœ… YesMass, Volume, Energy, Entropy

â­ Special Note

Extensive property / mass = Intensive property

Example:


Volume (extensive) / mass â†’ Specific volume (intensive)



