âœ… State Variables (State Functions)

State variables are properties that depend only on the current state of the system, not on how the system reached that state.

They are determined by state parameters like P, V, T.

Even if the path changes, the value remains the same for the same state.

Examples

Pressure (P)

Volume (V)

Temperature (T)

Internal energy (U)

Enthalpy (H)

Entropy (S)

Density (Ï)

Key Point

If initial and final states are same â†’ Change in state function = 0

âœ… Path Variables (Path Functions)

Path variables depend on the path or process by which a system changes from one state to another.

Their values are determined by how the process occurs, not just initial and final states.

Examples

Heat (Q)

Work (W)

Key Point

Diffrence table:

If path changes â†’ Heat & work change:

| Feature           | State Variables         | Path Variables   |
| ----------------- | ----------------------- | ---------------- |
| Depends on Path?  | âŒ No                    | âœ… Yes            |
| Depends on State? | âœ… Yes                   | âŒ No             |
| Symbol            | Usually capital letters | Q & W mainly     |
| Examples          | P, V, T, U, H, S        | Heat, Work       |
| Cyclic Process    | Î”(state function) = 0   | Total Q or W â‰  0 |


âœ… Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics

The Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics states that if two systems are each in thermal equilibrium with a third system, then they are also in thermal equilibrium with each other.

ğŸ”¥ Meaning

If A is in thermal equilibrium with C

And B is in thermal equilibrium with C

Then
â¡ï¸ A and B will be in thermal equilibrium with each other
â¡ï¸ So they have the same temperatur

âœ… Example

If a thermometer (C) is in thermal equilibrium with:

Hot water (A) â†’ thermometer shows high reading

Ice water (B) â†’ thermometer shows low reading

When thermometer shows same reading with both,
â¡ï¸ A and B are at the same temperature

âœ… Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics

If two bodies are each in thermal equilibrium with a third body, they are in thermal equilibrium with each other.

âœ… Defines temperature
âœ… Basis of thermometers
âœ… Lets us compare temperatures correctly

Example:
If Body A and Body B both have the same temperature as a thermometer (Body C), then A and B are at the same temperature.

âœ… First Law of Thermodynamics (Law of Energy Conservation)

Energy cannot be created or destroyed, only converted from one form to another.

In thermodynamics:

